You can use [django-tables2][1]. Install it and add it to `INSTALLED_APPS`. You&#39;ll also need to install `tablib` for the export feature. Create a `tables.py` file under your app folder:

```python
import django_tables2 as tables
from .models import Student

class StudentTable(tables.Table):
    export_formats = [&#39;xls&#39;, &#39;xlsx&#39;, &#39;csv&#39;]  # a list of formats you&#39;ll like to export to
    class Meta:
        model = Student
        fields = (&#39;name&#39;, &#39;mark&#39;)
        # There are more Meta attributes you can use, just look for them in the docs.
```

Then use the `SingleTableView` class with `ExportMixin` in your `views.py`:

```python
from django_tables2.views import SingleTableView
from django_tables2.export.views import ExportMixin
from .models import Student
from .tables import StudentTable

class StudentList(ExportMixin, SingleTableView):
    model = Student
    table_class = StudentTable
    export_name = &#39;students_assistance&#39;
    template_name = &#39;students/student_list.html&#39;
```

Finally your `student_list.html` template should look like this:

```html
{% load django_tables2 %}
&lt;div&gt;
  {% for format in table.export_formats %}
    &lt;a href=&quot;{% export_url format %}&quot;&gt;.{{ format }}&lt;/a&gt;
  {% endfor %}
&lt;/div&gt;
{% render_table table %}
```

There&#39;s a lot more you can do with `django-tables2`, this is just a basic implementation. You can also combine it with [django-filter][2].

[1]: https://django-tables2.readthedocs.io/en/latest/
[2]: https://django-filter.readthedocs.io/en/master/

